'''Ben Easter''' (born May 1, 1979) is an American actor and photographer.
Easter made his film debut in 2000 in ''[[Cora Unashamed]]''. He was later a repeated costar of the [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen twins]], appearing alongside them in the film ''[[Holiday in the Sun (film)|Holiday in the Sun]]'' and the television series ''[[So Little Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamour.com/entertainment/blogs/obsessed/2013/02/where-are-they-now-the-man-can|title=Where Are They Now: The Man Candy of Those Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen Movies|last=Brody|first=Caitlin|date=February 21, 2013|publisher=''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''|accessdate=2015-01-23}}</ref> He has also appeared in ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'', ''[[Zenon: Z3]]'', and ''[[I'll Always Know What You Did Last Summer]]''.
Easter began working as a professional photographer in 2008, and his photographs have since been featured in ''[[Icon (lifestyle magazine)|Icon]]'', ''Glamaholic'', ''Yoga Iowa'', and ''DSM Magazine''.<ref name="easter">{{cite web|url=http://www.beneasterphotography.com/bio|title=Ben Easter: Bio|date=2015|publisher=Ben Easter Photography|accessdate=2015-01-23}}</ref> An exhibit of his at the Polk County Jail in [[Des Moines, Iowa]], titled "Confliction", was later restaged in Paris by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://jcjusticecenter.com/2013/09/13/photo-exhibit-in-old-polk-county-iowa-jail-features-children-of-incarcerated-parents/|title = Photo Exhibit in Old Polk County Iowa Jail Features Children of Incarcerated Parents|date = September 13, 2013|website = Johnson County Justice Center|access-date = 2016-06-24}}</ref> He has worked for [[Wilhelmina Models]] and [[NEXT Model Management]], and was one of the photographers for the [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|2012 Obama presidential campaign]].<ref name="easter"/> In addition to his photography, Easter also works as a yoga instructor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iowasource.com/health/2011_10_yoga.html|title=Man Up! Yoga for Guys|last=Rinehart|first=Amy Scholl|date=November 2011|publisher=''The Iowa Source''|accessdate=2015-01-23}}</ref>
In 1998, Easter was selected as one of "America's Most Wanted Men" by ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dmcityview.com/2011/11/10/features/|title=Who are Des Moines’ sexiest people?|date=November 10, 2011|publisher=Des Moines CityView|accessdate=2015-01-23}}</ref>
